The New Mythic Dawn: The Architects of the Unmaking
Core Philosophy: The Liberation of Lorkhan
The cult in Skyrim does not view Mehrunes Dagon as a destroyer, but as the Prince of Hope. They believe, as Mankar Camoran did, that Tamriel is not a mortal plane, but a stolen Daedric Realm belonging to Lorkhan. The "Divines" (Aedra) are traitorous usurpers who betrayed Lorkhan and locked his realm into a stagnant, dying cycle of linear time and physics.
Their Goal: To shatter the "limiter" placed on the world by Akatosh and the Aedra. They want to return Nirn to the Dawn EraΓÇöa state of magical fluidity where thought shapes reality, where "mortals" regain their lost divinity as lesser Daedra, and where the "tyranny" of static existence is ended.
The Methodology: Nymic Surgery
The cultists do not just worship; they transform. Taking inspiration from Camoran's use of the Razor to reshape his own protonymic (true name), the elite members of the Skyrim cell practice Nymic Surgery.
They use lesser Daedric rituals to "cut" away parts of their mortal limitationsΓÇötheir need for sleep, their empathy, their physical fragility. This explains why high-ranking cultists like Gaelen have supernatural stats and bound armor; they have literally edited the source code of their own souls to be closer to Daedra.


Dagon Cult Session Clock: "The Unmaking" - GM Reference
Core Philosophy: The Dagon Cult seeks to complete the work Mankar Camoran began during the Oblivion Crisis. Their goal is not invasion, but transformation. By corrupting the three metaphysical "Pillars" of SkyrimΓÇöLife, Magic, and TimeΓÇöthey will create a province-wide ritual space. At the climax, they will use Mehrunes' Razor not to open a gate, but to sever Skyrim from Nirn, rewriting its natural laws and turning it into a permanent, ever-expanding pocket realm of the Deadlands.
Heroic Intervention: Destroying a "Seed of Desolation" or killing a named Dagon Cult "Prophet" postpones the next clock advancement by 2 full sessions.

