V. ALLIANCES & RIVALRIES
The Dragon Cult — Competing Apocalypse
The Dagon Cult and Dragon Cult are not allied. They are competing apocalypses with incompatible endgames.
Dragon Cult Objective: Reshape reality under Dragon Priest rule via Alduin's return. Stasis after destruction — a crystalline, unchanging new order.
Dagon Cult Objective: Unmake reality entirely, returning Skyrim to the chaotic fluidity of the Dawn Era. Constant change — no order, no stasis, only endless transformation.
Current Dynamic: They ignore each other where possible, but their operations interfere. The Eldergleam corruption (Dagon) actually helps Morokei by disrupting the College's leylines — an unintentional benefit the Dragon Cult exploits. However, Vlagoth's planned assault on the Time-Wound will be a declaration of war against the dragons. The two cults will clash openly on the slopes of the Throat of the World.
The Cult's View: "Let the lizards and their priests fight to preserve their dead king's dream. We will dance on the ashes of both their ambitions."
The Thalmor / Aldmeri Dominion — Opposing Apocalypse
The Thalmor are legitimate enemies of the Dagon Cult, not allies.
Thalmor Objective: Unbind reality through metaphysical manipulation of the Towers (the Tower Protocol). They want to collapse Mundus on their terms, preserving Elven souls in a new divine form.
Dagon Cult Objective: Unmake reality through Daedric ritual (the Razor). They want to return to the Dawn Era's chaos, where there are no Elves, no Men, no distinction — only endless change.
Conflict: These are incompatible endgames. The Thalmor want controlled unbinding; the Dagon Cult want total unmaking. The Thalmor hunt Dagon Cultists as heretics. The Dagon Cult views the Thalmor as "statists" clinging to a racial hierarchy that Dagon's chaos would erase.
Current Dynamic: The Thalmor's focus on the Wardens and the dragon threat has drawn their attention away from the Dagon Cult. This is temporary. Elenwen has begun receiving reports of "red-robed fanatics" in the Rift and Eastmarch. Thalmor-Dagon conflict is inevitable.
Valerius & The Pale Court — Parallel but Unrelated
Valerius wants a fractured, desperate Skyrim — which the Dagon Cult's operations inadvertently provide. However, there is no coordination.
Valerius's Goal: Political control of Skyrim through vampiric infiltration.
Dagon Cult's Goal: The end of political control entirely — the dissolution of all hierarchies into chaotic freedom.
Dynamic: Valerius benefits from the chaos the Dagon Cult creates, but he would be destroyed along with everyone else if the Unmaking succeeds. He is an unwitting beneficiary, not an ally.
Hircine — Complicated Relationship
The Dagon Cult's corruption of nature has attracted Hircine's attention — not as an ally, but as a competitor.
Hircine's View: The corrupted forests and mutated animals of Eastmarch are "interesting" but not "true" nature. Hircine values the hunt, the cycle of predator and prey. The Dagon Cult's chaos removes all cycles — everything becomes random mutation, not evolution.
Saijah's Crossroads: Hircine has offered Saijah power to "save" the Eldergleam by hunting and killing Gaelen. This is not altruism — Hircine wants to claim the corrupted grove as his hunting ground, replacing Dagon's chaos with his own brand of predatory order.
Cult's View: Hircine is "a dog who thinks he owns the forest we are burning." They do not fear him, but they are aware that his interference could complicate the Second and Third Pillars.
